Supervised Learning - Foundations Project: ReCell¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Buying and selling used phones and tablets used to be something that happened on a handful of online marketplace sites. But the used and refurbished device market has grown considerably over the past decade, and a new IDC (International Data Corporation) forecast predicts that the used phone market would be worth \$52.7bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 13.6% from 2018 to 2023. This growth can be attributed to an uptick in demand for used phones and tablets that offer considerable savings compared with new models.

Refurbished and used devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses that are looking to save money when purchasing one. There are plenty of other benefits associated with the used device market. Used and refurbished devices can be sold with warranties and can also be insured with proof of purchase. Third-party vendors/platforms, such as Verizon, Amazon, etc., provide attractive offers to customers for refurbished devices. Maximizing the longevity of devices through second-hand trade also reduces their environmental impact and helps in recycling and reducing waste. The impact of the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost this segment as consumers cut back on discretionary spending and buy phones and tablets only for immediate needs.

Objective¶

The rising potential of this comparatively under-the-radar market fuels the need for an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished devices. ReCell, a startup aiming to tap the potential in this market, has hired you as a data scientist. They want you to analyze the data provided and build a linear regression model to predict the price of a used phone/tablet and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used/refurbished phones and tablets. The data was collected in the year 2021. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the device runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the device battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the device in grams
  • release_year: Year when the device model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished device has been used
  • normalized_new_price: Normalized price of a new device of the same model in euros
  • normalized_used_price: Normalized price of the used/refurbished device in euros

Several numeric columns have missing values:

Categorical Variables:

brand_name: 34 unique brands; most frequent is “Others” (502 entries).

os: 4 categories, “Android” dominates (3,214 out of 3,454).

4g and 5g: binary categories (yes/no), majority of devices are not 5G capable (3,302 are “no”).

Screen Size:

Mean: ~13.7 cm, Range: 5.08 cm – 30.71 cm.

Camera Features:

main_camera_mp: average ~9.5 MP, maximum 48 MP.

selfie_camera_mp: average ~6.5 MP, max 32 MP, but includes zeros and missing values.

Memory and RAM:

int_memory: wide spread from 0.01 GB to 1024 GB (likely some outliers).

ram: centered around 4 GB, max 12 GB.

Battery & Weight:

battery: ranges from 500 mAh to 9,720 mAh — may require outlier treatment.

weight: average ~183g, but spans from 69g to 855g — another candidate for outlier check.

Device Age:

release_year: 2013–2020.

days_used: mean ~ 675 days (~1.8 years); range from 91 to 1,094 days.

Target Variable (normalized_used_price):

Mean: ~4.36 euros (normalized), range: 1.54 – 6.62.

The data appears to be skewed right, which we will verify in the distribution plot.

New Price:

Mean: ~5.23 euros (normalized), range: 2.90 – 7.85.

This data is useful for comparison and likely to be a strong predictor.

  7. Which attributes are highly correlated with the normalized price of a used device?

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

This heatmap highlights the Pearson correlation coefficients between all continuous numerical variables in the dataset.

Values close to +1 indicate strong positive relationships, while those near -1 indicate strong negative relationships.

Key Insights:¶

  • High Correlation with Used Price (normalized_used_price):

    • normalized_new_price shows a strong positive correlation (0.83), indicating new price is a key determinant of used price.

    • main_camera_mp (0.59), selfie_camera_mp (0.61), ram (0.52), and battery (0.61) all positively correlate with used price, suggesting that better specifications generally lead to higher resale values.

    • screen_size (0.61) also has a strong positive link with used price.

  • Negative Correlation with days_used:

    • days_used negatively correlates with normalized_used_price (-0.36) and release_year (-0.75), indicating that older and longer-used devices depreciate more.

  • Inter-feature Correlations:

    • screen_size is strongly correlated with battery (0.81) and weight (0.83), which is expected as larger devices typically have larger batteries and are heavier.

    • selfie_camera_mp and release_year (0.69) have a strong positive relationship, hinting that newer models are more likely to have better selfie cameras.

Implications for Modeling:¶

  • normalized_new_price, camera specs, battery, and RAM should be considered important predictors for modeling used prices.

  • Be cautious of multicollinearity in features like screen_size, battery, and weight, as they are strongly inter-correlated.

cols_impute = [
    "main_camera_mp",
    "selfie_camera_mp",
    "int_memory",
    "ram",
    "battery",
    "weight",
]

# imputing missing values with grouped median
for col in cols_impute:
    df1[col] = df1[col].fillna(
        value=df1.groupby(['release_year', 'brand_name'])[col].transform("median")
    )  ## Impute using grouped medians

Missing Value Imputation (Grouped by Release Year & Brand Name)¶

cols_impute = [

Outlier Handling Strategy (Comments Post Evaluation of entire model)¶

Although several numeric features (e.g., battery, weight, internal memory) display visible outliers, no formal outlier treatment (such as removal, transformation, or capping) was applied in this project. This decision is based on the following:

  • The model performed well on both train and test sets (R² > 0.83, MAPE < 5%), indicating that outliers did not harm predictive power.
  • Missing values were imputed using median-based strategies, which are inherently robust to outliers.
  • Outlier thresholds vary by context — for example, a device with 8000+ mAh battery or 512 GB storage may still be valid in the refurbished market.

Model Performance Check¶

Now that we've trained the OLS regression model, it's time to evaluate how well it performs on the test set.

We will calculate the following metrics:

  • RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): Measures the average magnitude of prediction errors.
  • MAE (Mean Absolute Error): Captures the average of the absolute errors.
  • R² (Coefficient of Determination): Explains how much variance in the target is captured by the model.
  • MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error): Expresses prediction error as a percentage of actual values.
  • Adjusted R²: Adjusts R² based on the number of predictors in the model.

We will:

  • Use sklearn.metrics for RMSE, MAE, and R²
  • Define a custom function to compute MAPE and Adjusted R²
  • Wrap all of these into a single utility function to evaluate our model efficiently
In [712]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score

# Adjusted R²
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))

# MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100

# Performance Metrics
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    pred = model.predict(predictors) if hasattr(model, 'predict') else model.predict(exog=predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)

    return pd.DataFrame({
        "RMSE": [rmse],
        "MAE": [mae],
        "R-squared": [r2],
        "Adj. R-squared": [adjr2],
        "MAPE": [mape]
    })

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  • In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.
  • We will be checking the following Linear Regression assumptions:

  1. No Multicollinearity

  2. Linearity of variables

  3. Independence of error terms

  4. Normality of error terms

  5. No Heteroscedasticity

TEST FOR MULTICOLLINEARITY¶

  • We will test for multicollinearity using VIF.

  • General Rule of thumb:

    • If VIF is 1 then there is no correlation between the $k$th predictor and the remaining predictor variables.
    • If VIF exceeds 5 or is close to exceeding 5, we say there is moderate multicollinearity.
    • If VIF is 10 or exceeding 10, it shows signs of high multicollinearity.
In [720]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

def checking_vif(predictors):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = predictors.columns

    # calculating VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(predictors.values, i)
        for i in range(len(predictors.columns))
    ]
    return vif

We evaluated multicollinearity using Variance Inflation Factor (VIF):

Key Observations:¶

  • normalized_new_price has an extremely high VIF of 152.25, suggesting strong multicollinearity with other variables (likely has_4g, has_5g, screen_size, etc.).
  • screen_size, ram, battery, and years_since_release also show moderate to high VIFs (above 10), indicating potential redundancy.
  • Binary features has_4g and has_5g show infinite VIF, likely due to perfect collinearity with other encoded versions or being perfectly correlated with each other.
  • has_selfie_camera also shows high VIF (108), suggesting it's highly correlated with another feature (possibly selfie_camera_mp).
  • Many brand_name_ and os_ dummies show acceptable VIF values below 5, though a few (like brand_name_Apple, brand_name_Samsung, and os_iOS) cross that threshold slightly.

Next Steps (Recommendations):¶

  • Look at dropping or combining variables with high multicollinearity:
    • Drop either has_5g/has_4g or use only one flag.
    • Drop normalized_new_price if it's too tightly coupled with other predictors.
    • Evaluate whether has_selfie_camera is needed if selfie_camera_mp is already used.

I will then rerun the regression after simplifying features to improve model stability and interpretability.

Removing Multicollinearity (its needed)¶

To remove multicollinearity

  1. Drop every column one by one that has a VIF score greater than 5.
  2. Please review the adjusted R-squared and RMSE for all these models.
  3. Please remove the variable that results in the smallest change in adjusted R-squared.
  4. Check the VIF scores again.
  5. Continue until you get all VIF scores under 5.

Let's define a function that will help us do this.

In [725]:
def treating_multicollinearity(predictors, target, high_vif_columns):
    """
    Checking the effect of dropping the columns showing high multicollinearity
    on model performance (adj. R-squared and RMSE)

    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    high_vif_columns: columns having high VIF
    """
    # empty lists to store adj. R-squared and RMSE values
    adj_r2 = []
    rmse = []

    # build ols models by dropping one of the high VIF columns at a time
    # store the adjusted R-squared and RMSE in the lists defined previously
    for cols in high_vif_columns:
        # defining the new train set
        train = predictors.loc[:, ~predictors.columns.str.startswith(cols)]

        # create the model
        olsmodel = sm.OLS(target, train).fit()

        # adding adj. R-squared and RMSE to the lists
        adj_r2.append(olsmodel.rsquared_adj)
        rmse.append(np.sqrt(olsmodel.mse_resid))

    # creating a dataframe for the results
    temp = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "col": high_vif_columns,
            "Adj. R-squared after_dropping col": adj_r2,
            "RMSE after dropping col": rmse,
        }
    ).sort_values(by="Adj. R-squared after_dropping col", ascending=False)
    temp.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

    return temp

Multicollinearity Treatment Summary¶

To improve the reliability and interpretability of our linear regression model, I performed a multicollinearity check using the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF). High VIF values indicate that a feature is highly correlated with other predictors, which can inflate standard errors and make p-values unreliable.

Steps Taken:¶

  • Calculated VIF for all predictors.
  • Identified features with VIF > 5 (moderate) and > 10 (severe multicollinearity).
  • Iteratively dropped features with the highest VIF (e.g., screen_size, os_iOS, brand_name_Others) while monitoring model performance.
  • Recalculated VIF after each step to ensure that remaining predictors were not highly correlated.

Why I Did This:¶

  • To reduce redundancy in the model.
  • To improve the statistical significance of individual coefficients.
  • To ensure more stable and interpretable model outputs.

This process ensures that each feature contributes unique, non-overlapping information to the model — aligning with best practices in statistical modeling.

“Build a linear regression model to predict the price of used devices and identify which features most influence price.”

This goal explicitly requires both accurate prediction and interpretability.

Dropping high p-value variables (if needed)¶

  • We will drop the predictor variables having a p-value greater than 0.05 as they do not significantly impact the target variable.
  • But sometimes p-values change after dropping a variable. So, we'll not drop all variables at once.
  • Instead, we will do the following:
    • Build a model, check the p-values of the variables, and drop the column with the highest p-value.
    • Create a new model without the dropped feature, check the p-values of the variables, and drop the column with the highest p-value.
    • Repeat the above two steps till there are no columns with p-value > 0.05.

The above process can also be done manually by picking one variable at a time that has a high p-value, dropping it, and building a model again. But that might be a little tedious and using a loop will be more efficient.

max_p_value = 1

while len(cols) > 0:
    x_train_aux = predictors[cols]
    model = sm.OLS(y_train, x_train_aux).fit()
    p_values = model.pvalues
    max_p_value = max(p_values)
    feature_with_p_max = p_values.idxmax()

    if max_p_value > 0.05:
        cols.remove(feature_with_p_max)
    else:
        break

TEST FOR LINEARITY AND INDEPENDENCE¶

  • We will test for linearity and independence by making a plot of fitted values vs residuals and checking for patterns.
  • If there is no pattern, then we say the model is linear and residuals are independent.
  • Otherwise, the model is showing signs of non-linearity and residuals are not independent.

Test for Linearity and Independence of Residuals¶

To check the assumptions of linearity and independence, I plotted the residuals vs. fitted values.

  • Linearity: The residuals are mostly randomly scattered around zero, with no strong non-linear pattern. This suggests that the relationship between the predictors and the response is approximately linear.

  • Independence: The spread of residuals appears consistent across all fitted values, and no clusters or trends are observed. This indicates independence of residuals.

  • The LOWESS (red) line remains close to the horizontal axis, further supporting both assumptions.

Conclusion: The model satisfies the assumptions of linearity and independence of errors.

TEST FOR NORMALITY¶

  • We will test for normality by checking the distribution of residuals, by checking the Q-Q plot of residuals, and by using the Shapiro-Wilk test.
  • If the residuals follow a normal distribution, they will make a straight line plot, otherwise not.
  • If the p-value of the Shapiro-Wilk test is greater than 0.05, we can say the residuals are normally distributed.

Test for Normality of Residuals¶

I assessed the normality of residuals using three methods:

  • Histogram: The residuals showed a roughly bell-shaped, symmetric distribution.
  • Q-Q Plot: Most points aligned well with the theoretical normal line, except for slight deviation in the tails.
  • Shapiro-Wilk Test:
    • Statistic: 0.9649
    • p-value: 8.77e-24

Interpretation:¶

  • The very low p-value suggests a statistically significant deviation from normality.
  • However, with a large sample size (n = 2417), even small deviations can result in a low p-value.
  • Visual inspection indicates that residuals are approximately normal, which is generally acceptable in linear regression.

Conclusion: While the residuals are not perfectly normal, their distribution is close enough to satisfy the assumption for linear regression in this context.

Test for Homescedastiscity¶

  • We will test for homoscedasticity by using the goldfeldquandt test.
  • If we get a p-value greater than 0.05, we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic. Otherwise, they are heteroscedastic.

Test for Homoscedasticity (Goldfeld–Quandt Test)¶

I tested for homoscedasticity, which refers to the assumption that the variance of the residuals is constant across all levels of the independent variables.

Method:¶

  • Used the Goldfeld–Quandt test.
  • Null Hypothesis (H₀): Residuals have constant variance (homoscedastic).
  • Alternative Hypothesis (H₁): Residuals have non-constant variance (heteroscedastic).

Results:¶

  • F-statistic: 0.9642
  • p-value: 0.7355

Interpretation:¶

  • Since the p-value > 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.
  • This confirms that the residuals are homoscedastic, fulfilling this assumption of linear regression.

Final Model Summary¶

The final model was developed after addressing multicollinearity (using VIF) and removing high p-value predictors.

A total of 14 predictors were retained, all statistically significant (p-value < 0.05).

Key insights:

  • normalized_new_price (coef = 0.4168) is the strongest predictor, indicating that the original retail price has a large positive effect on used phone price.

  • Features like weight, main_camera_mp, and ram have positive influence on used price.

  • Features such as years_since_release and has_selfie_camera show negative associations.

  • High and consistent R-squared values between training and testing data suggest a good generalization of the model.

  • MAPE < 5% confirms excellent predictive accuracy.

  • No signs of overfitting detected.

Conclusion

  • This is a strong and reliable linear regression model for predicting the normalized used price of phones. It:

  • Meets all linear regression assumptions,

  • Maintains high predictive integrity,

And is ready to support business decisions related to used device pricing.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Business Recommendations Based on Final Model¶

Based on the insights from the final linear regression model, the following business recommendations are suggested for ReCell:

1. Focus on Devices with Higher New Price¶

  • Devices with higher normalized new prices tend to retain more of their value in the used market.
  • Strategy: Prioritize sourcing and marketing flagship and premium models for better resale margins.

2. Promote Devices with Strong Camera Capabilities¶

  • Both main camera and selfie camera megapixels significantly impact used price.
  • Strategy: Highlight camera specifications prominently in listings and promotional material, especially for selfie-centric devices.

3. Target Devices with Higher RAM and Storage¶

  • Devices with higher RAM and internal memory correlate with better resale value.
  • Strategy: Focus on acquiring mid-to-high range configurations (e.g., 6GB+ RAM, 128GB+ storage) as they command higher prices.

4. Consider Device Weight and Build¶

  • Interestingly, heavier devices (possibly more robust or larger battery) are priced higher in the used market.
  • Strategy: Use weight and battery size as selling points for specific customer segments like travelers and power users.

5. Account for Age of Device¶

  • Older devices (more years since release) negatively impact resale price.
  • Strategy: Implement dynamic pricing strategies to aggressively discount and clear older inventory.

6. Operating System Matters¶

  • Devices with operating systems categorized as “Others” (non-Android/iOS) are priced significantly lower.
  • Strategy: Avoid sourcing obscure OS devices; focus on mainstream platforms to ensure resale value.

7. 4G and 5G Trends¶

  • 4G support slightly boosts price; however, 5G support shows a small negative impact, possibly due to limited current demand or higher expectations.
  • Strategy: Monitor market trends. As 5G adoption grows, this dynamic may shift—adjust sourcing accordingly.

These recommendations can guide procurement, pricing, and marketing strategies to improve profitability and customer satisfaction in ReCell’s used device marketplace.
